-----<br>
<br>
This sum up the complaints I have about DAOC. You are happy and have fun because you are in one of the rare servers when midgard actually has the upper hand.<br>
<br>
End game is RvR. When you are in a server where you are thoroughly dominated, out manned, out gunned, and zerged to death, end game is not fun. If only the &quot;one hib dead for one mid dead&quot; ratio was true, I could have fun.<br>
<br>
When the game is not fun, it's time to move on.<br>
<br>
As for the skald class :<br>
The ones having fun with it seem to be the gank group veterans, who have lived in emain and the gorge for the past 6 months, who have dependable groups, buckets of RPs and know every tree in the golf course. To this kind of single, &quot;elite&quot; group, the skald is a great asset, one of the most powerful class in the game.<br>
<br>
80% of the skalds lack either the time, the dedication to be part of those elite gank squads regular, or simply, like me, don't simply like a RvR that consists of small group vs. small group engagments. Of course this a great way to play the game, it requires a degree of skill that I admire and envy, and in some nice battle, the adrenaline rush is worth everything. However, what I bought DAOC for was not the guerilla warfare in the gorge, however fun it maybe for a skilled skald, but I envisioned a game with large scale battles, armies, epic sieges. I can bet many of the &quot;elite&quot; skalds on the boards despise and dislike the &quot;zerg&quot;, and to an extent I do agree with them, because this part of the game is not fun the way it is.<br>
However, I still want(ed) to be a part of this kind of RvR'ing. I wanted to experience large scale engagments. I dreamed about colorful keep assault.<br>
I am one of those &quot;looking for group&quot; skalds in the large zerg forces, that don't have a permanent of semi permanent &quot;gank squad&quot; like the one that earns the big realm points on my servers. I see nothing wrong with me lagging in power  behind those skalds (though I really would like some token RPs for the dozens of hours spent attacking or defending keeps ...).<br>
However, for the skald class ... this is really day and night. The skald shine as much in small group engagments as it flatly suck in large scale battles and keep sieging/defense.<br>
After a thorough reflexion, I think I have chosen the wrong class, for my playstyle, goals, and habits. Which is pretty ironic, because I originally thought skalds, as a &quot;support&quot; class, would only grow better the more people with them in their group of raid.<br>
I sincerely wish I had chosen a caster with some degree of AE damage dealing ability, or a shaman, or assassin, or something that could matter when behind the walls of a keep.<br>
<br>
This is just what I wanted to say about the skald class. With the feedback and experience of 1 year of playing, it is pretty obvious some classes are better suited for certain playstyle, and at the time (2 weeks after release) I chose my class, I did pick wrong. This is not the fault of the class itself, only mine, though I wonder how, with my limited experience and knowledge of the game, I would have known better at this time.<br>
<br>
However, there still one thing the skald community or rosey should strive for. <br>
Make the class useful (not overpowerful. Simply useful) in the various aspects of RvR, for both &quot;new&quot; and &quot;experienced&quot; skalds alike. Never like the class sink completely into this pigeonhole. The one trick pony. The fact that the skald shines as a part of the elite small group battles shouldn't mask the fact that, for the newer skald, or for the skald that want to take part in a more large scale battle- and keep-oriented RvR, life can suck, badly. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#efe0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dane@teamskald>Dane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Fervent</span><br>  Posts: 101<br> <font color=#ff0000>(12/5/02 3:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=413.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Role</span><hr size=1> PvE: Obvious.  Damage add, runspeed, support damage, light tank (red and below is tolerable, even purps fully geared at 50...but mana spongy), great puller, good peeler with mezz. <br>
<br>
RvR:<br>
Premeir caster killer.  As someone mentioned, it's pretty easy, you just get &quot;out of view&quot; to them when they cast...even with /face if you time it right, you can kill them without getting hit in many cases.  You can also mezz one caster, and do the dancing with another...2 caster neutralized basically in seconds.  Hell, while you're killing the mezzd one, snare some archer and screw up his bow shot, and prep him for the chasedown that will follow....<br>
<br>
Assassin killer: When assassins pop, bang on them with DDs and 2H from behind or side.  They cant evade, and they take insane damage from 2H, especially you hammer skalds.  You can hang with them if they turn to fight.  Doing this to, say, a polermsman, would be less successfull...or worse, a paladin :/<br>
And if they are hitting your healer or a mage...just mezz peel.  Your healer or mage is instantly free to cast.  Ever try to kill an enemey before they kill RM or SM pal?  Yeah, mezz makes you one of the better peelers in midgard.<br>
<br>
Only counter to SOS and other runspeed classes.  That bard getting away?  Who's gonna stop him?  YOU!  Chase him down and teach him a lesson.  Minstrel SOS?  Tail him..wait..............snare and kill.  He blew SOS and still gave you RPs...always nice.  With endurance regen it's even easier to chasedown.  Good at killing bards...OK at killing minstrels.<br>
<br>
Archer killer.  Snare as you approach...then commence killing as per usual.  Have you ever been killed by an archer when you weren't preoccupied with someone else?  I haven't that I can recall...<br>
<br>
So you don't excel at taking out tank hybrids and tanks, but you do just fine vs everyone else.  You have no equal vs mages, that alone is a nice benefit to a group.  Sure, the occassional MOC can screw you up, but your IP screws with them just as readily.<br>
<br>
We DO need stackable and dual resist chants IMO, currently, the are next to useless.<br>
<br>
<br>
In ANY large scale battle, you are also the premeir sweeper.  You are the leader in the chasedowns, those easiest of easy RPs that you get on 10 fleeing enemies.<br>
<br>
In any standoff, where say the enemy is assembled near your keep, but starts to move off to a non-defended one.....speed/sprint up to them, snare a mage at 1500, B-line back to your keep.  They aren't going to leave that snared mage behind ususally...they only half trickle off....do it again....get your skald buddy next to you to do the same...at some point you can be soley responsible for halting an organzined tactical enemy retreat, and for spreading their force out as your force comes in for the kill.<br>
<br>
That's just a few off the top of my head.<br>
<br>
-Dane <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c2a2><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mance>Mance</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Contributor</span><br>  Posts: 96<br> <font color=#ff0000>(12/5/02 5:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=413.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Role</span><hr size=1> I actually prefer &quot;zerg&quot; or big fights, that's were skalds are the most fun imho.<br>
